solution.p:
We first collect all the variable terms on one side of the equation, and the constant terms on the other side.
        
            
                3x - 5 \alert{{}- x} \amp = x + 3 \alert{{}- x}\amp\amp \text{Subtract }x \text{ from both sides.}
            
            
                2x - 5 \amp = 3\amp\amp \text{Simplify.}
            
            
                2x - 5 \alert{{}+ 5} \amp = 3 \alert{{}+ 5}\amp\amp \text{Add 5 to both sides.}
            
            
                2x \amp = 8 \amp\amp\text{Simplify.}
            
            
                \frac{2x}{\alert{2}}\amp =\frac{8}{\alert{2}}\amp\amp\text{Divide both sides by 2.}
            
            
                x\amp = 4\amp\amp\text{Simplify.}
            
            
        The solution is 4. (You can check the solution by substituting 4 into the original equation to show that you get a true statement as the result.)

We begin by simplifying each side of the equation.
    
        
            3(2x - 5) - 4x \amp = 2x - (6 - 3x) \amp\amp\text{Apply the distributive law.}
        
        
            6x - 15 - 4x \amp= 2x - 6 + 3x \amp\amp\text{Combine like terms on each side.}
        
        
            2x - 15 \amp= 5x - 6
        
    
    Next, we collect all the variable terms on the left side of the equation, and all the constant terms on the right side.
    
        
            2x - 15 \alert{- 5x} \amp= 5x - 6 \alert{- 5x} \amp\amp\text{Subtract }5x \text{ from both sides.}
        
        
            -3x - 15 \alert{+ 15} \amp= - 6 \alert{+ 15} \amp\amp\text{Add } 15 \text{ to both sides.}
        
        
            -3x \amp= 9
        
    
    Finally, we divide both sides of the equation by the coefficient of the variable.
    
        
            -3x \amp= 9 \amp\amp\text{Divide both sides by }-3.
        
        
            x \amp =-3
        
    
    The solution is -3.

We begin by finding the least common multiple of the three denominators: LCM(3,4,2)=12. Then we multiply both sides of the equation by 12, and continue solving as normal.
\begin{aligned} \frac{p-2}{3}+\frac{p}{4}\amp =\frac{1}{2}\\ (\alert{12})\left(\frac{p-2}{3}+\frac{p}{4}\right)\amp =(\alert{12})\frac{1}{2}\\ \frac{12(p-2)}{3}+\frac{12p}{4}\amp =\frac{12}{2}\\ 4(p-2)+3p\amp =6\\ 4p-8+3p\amp =6\\ 7p-8\amp = 6\\ 7p\amp =14\\ p\amp =2 \end{aligned}
The solution is p=2.

As always, our first step is to combine like terms.
\begin{aligned} 0.04x+0.08x \amp= -0.1+0.17x \\ 0.12x \amp= -0.1+0.17x \end{aligned}
Since the decimal coefficients have up to 2 decimal places, we will multiply each side of the equation by 100 before solving the equation.
\begin{aligned} 0.12x \amp =-0.1+0.17x\\ (\alert{100})(0.12x) \amp =(\alert{100})(-0.1+0.17x)\\ 2x\amp =-10+17x\\ -5x\amp =-10\\ x\amp =2 \end{aligned}
The solution is x=2.

solution.me:
\begin{aligned}
    y \amp= 3(x+8) \amp\amp\text{Apply the distributive property.} \\
    y \amp= 3x+24 \amp\amp\text{Subtract 24 from both sides.} \\
    y-24 \amp= 3x\amp\amp\text{Divide by 3.} \\
    \dfrac{y-24}{3} \amp= x
\end{aligned}

subsection.p:
Suppose we have some wire fence to enclose an exercise area for rabbits, and we would like to see what dimensions are possible for different rectangles with that perimeter. In this case, it would be more useful to have a formula for the length of the rectangle in terms of its perimeter and its width. We can find such a formula by solving the perimeter formula for L in terms of P and W.

    
        2L + 2W \amp= P \amp\amp\text{Subtract }2W \text{ from both sides}
    
    
        2L \amp= P - 2W \amp\amp\text{Divide both sides by 2}
    
    
        L \amp= \frac{P - 2W}{2}
    

The result is a new formula that gives the length of a rectangle in terms of its perimeter and its width.

The symbol \gt is called an inequality symbolinequality symbol, and the statement a\gt b is called an inequalityinequality. There are four inequality symbols:

    
        \amp\gt \amp\amp\text{is greater than}
    
    
        \amp\lt \amp\amp\text{is less than}
    
    
        \amp\ge \amp\amp\text{is greater than or equal to}
    
    
        \amp\le \amp\amp\text{is less than or equal to}

